{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01ESpPm4jpWdoLgs89qNvRjc","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to generate 10 realistic fake OCR recipe text files. Let me break down the requirements:\n\n1. **File format**: Save to `tools/title-loop/input/{RECIPE_TITLE}.generated.22.txt`\n\n2. **Filename rules**:\n   - Use SPACES, not hyphens or underscores\n   - Preserve Polish diacritics (e.g., \"Żurek.generated.22.txt\")\n   - Filename title must EXACTLY match the main title in text (case-insensitive OK)\n\n3. **Recipe mix**:\n   - ~60% English, ~40% Polish\n   - Variety: soups, mains, desserts, salads, appetizers, breads, drinks, preserves\n   - Mix of multi-word (2-5 words) and single-word titles\n\n4. **Must avoid these recipes**: (provided list of ~80 existing recipes)\n\n5. **Pattern requirements for batch**:\n   - 4 files with SPLIT_TITLE: Title split across 2-4 lines, 1-2 words per line\n   - 4 files with NARRATIVE: 3-7 lines of prose/cooking story between title and ingredients\n   - 2 files with SIMPLE: Basic OCR noise, stray numbers, page headers, broken words\n\n6. **File length**: 15-60 lines, spillover files 40-60 lines\n\nLet me pick 10 unique recipes that aren't in the excluded list:\n\nEnglish recipes (6-7):\n1. Butternut Squash Risotto (Spillover - narrative style) - 50 lines\n2. Lemon Herb Roasted Vegetables (Simple) - 30 lines\n3. Mixed Berry Jam (Split title) - 25 lines\n4. Creamy Mushroom Pasta (Narrative) - 45 lines\n5. Rosemary Focaccia Bread (Split title) - 35 lines\n\n\n6. Grilled Salmon with Dill (Simple) - 28 lines\n\nPolish recipes (3-4):\n7. Zupa Jarzynowa (Narrative - split title) - 40 lines\n8. Sernik Tradycyjny (Narrative) - 35 lines\n9. Piernik Miodowy (Split title) - 30 lines\n10. Kopytka z Grzybami (Simple) - 32 lines\n\nI need to double-check the excluded list to ensure none of these overlap, then start generating the files with appropriate OCR artifacts and formatting for each pattern type. ony** (Polish, Soup) - SIMPLE, 26 lines\n\nI need to verify the excluded Polish recipes more carefully. The list includes multiple piernik variations, kopytka preparations, placki owocowe, and żurek versions, so I should select recipes that don't overlap with those. Let me compile a fresh set of 10 recipes that avoids all duplicates from the excluded list.\n\nThe selection includes butternut squash risotto and lemon herb roasted vegetables as English dishes, mixed berry jam as a preserve, creamy mushroom pasta and grilled salmon with dill as mains, rosemary focaccia for bread, and żurek litewski, kopytka z cebulą, makowiec, and barszcz czerwony representing Polish cuisine. This gives me 6 English and 4 Polish recipes. I notice the format distribution needs adjustment—I have 4 narrative formats, 3 simple, and only 3 split_title formats when I need 4 of the latter and 2 of the simple. Żurek Litewski** - SPLIT_TITLE (38 lines)\n8. **Kopytka z Cebulą** - SIMPLE (32 lines)\n9. **Makowiec** - SPLIT_TITLE (35 lines)\n10. **Barszcz Czerwony** - SIMPLE (26 lines)\n\nI'm still one short on NARRATIVE and one over on SIMPLE. Let me shift #8 to NARRATIVE instead, which gives me the right distribution across all three formats.\n\n1. **Butternut Squash Risotto** - NARRATIVE (50 lines)\n2. **Lemon Herb Roasted Vegetables** - SIMPLE (28 lines)\n3. **Mixed Berry Jam** - SPLIT_TITLE (25 lines)\n4. **Creamy Mushroom Pasta** - NARRATIVE (45 lines)\n5. **Rosemary Focaccia Bread** - SPLIT_TITLE (35 lines)\n6. **Grilled Salmon with Dill** - NARRATIVE (40 lines)\n7. **Żurek Litewski** - SPLIT_TITLE (38 lines)\n8. **Kopytka z Cebulą** - NARRATIVE (32 lines)\n9. **Makowiec** - SPLIT_TITLE (35 lines)\n10. **Barszcz Czerwony** - SIMPLE (26 lines)\n\nNow I have four SPLIT_TITLE recipes, four NARRATIVE, and two SIMPLE—exactly what's needed. The language balance also works with English recipes at positions #1 and #2.\n\nFor the OCR simulation, I need to incorporate realistic scanning artifacts: character substitutions like 0 for O or l for I, page headers, ingredient measurements, cooking instructions, and occasional word breaks. SPLIT_TITLE recipes will have titles fragmented across multiple lines, while NARRATIVE recipes will include introductory prose before the structured recipe content.\n\nI'm ready to generate all 10 files using the Write tool, mixing in OCR noise patterns—character confusion (O/0, l/1, rn/m, S/5), irregular line breaks, spacing inconsistencies, and page markers—while keeping some sections clean to reflect variable scan quality.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":88150,"cache_read_input_tokens":15568,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":88150},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"10f3291a-c249-48df-81bc-02c14533ee15","uuid":"3543f86d-857f-4aae-a45c-f6849c672a9f"}
